## SERP ANALYSIS

**Blog Gen Instruction:** The SERP data below reveals where competitors are thin and where we win. Use the gaps to drive structure and content depth. Our differentiation is knowing this audience better — not matching competitor length.

### Competitor Summary

**Common H2 topics competitors cover (baseline — do not simply replicate these):**
- What are velvet nails?
- Velvet vs cat eye — the difference
- How to create velvet nails at home (technique)
- Products needed (magnetic gel, magnet wand)
- Best colours for velvet nails
- Winter/holiday velvet inspo
- Velvet nail gallery (undifferentiated)
- Velvet French tips
- Dark velvet nails
- Longevity and care tips

**Content approach and weaknesses:** Most competitors approach velvet nails as either a technique explainer (Amedo Beauty, Scratch Magazine, Classique Supply) or an undifferentiated gallery (naildesigns4u, Byrdie roundups, InStyle listicles). They cover "what it is" and "how it's made" adequately but fail to give the reader a confident decision framework — designs are presented without helping the reader understand which look is right for their colouring, occasion, or aesthetic direction. Marie Claire (Feb 2026) came closest to editorial authority but stopped short of colour-story organisation and skin tone guidance. The inspirational curation gap is wide open.

**Visual patterns:** Gallery-format competitors use 20–30 images; editorial posts like Marie Claire use 8–10. Given the inspirational intent and design diversity required, 10–12 is the sweet spot.

**Recommended image count:** 10–12 images — one per major design direction and colour story to give genuine gallery authority without overwhelming.

### Competitor Gaps

**Unanswered questions competitors are NOT addressing:**
- "Do velvet nails work in summer or are they only a winter finish?" — every source frames velvet as winter/holiday; 2026 editorial (Zoe Report, Joyee Nails, Marie Claire) explicitly confirms year-round relevance in lighter tones
- "Which velvet colours actually suit my skin tone?" — almost entirely absent from all gallery posts
- "What nail shape makes velvet nails look best?" — shape guidance missing; almond's relationship to velvet never made explicit
- "Can I wear velvet nails to work or will it look too much?" — workplace wearability completely unaddressed
- "What is the difference between velvet plaid, velvet swirls, and velvet French tips — which looks most expensive?" — design hierarchy and sub-category organisation nowhere present
- "Do velvet nails require a UV lamp or can I do them with regular polish?" — gel vs regular polish distinction rarely clarified with clarity

**Missing semantic territory:**
- Velvet design sub-categories (plaid, swirls, ombré, French tips) rarely organised for the reader as distinct choices
- Colour-by-season pairing logic
- Quiet luxury / old money framing — 2026 celebrity nail artists (Gerstein, Kandalec) cite understated taupes and silvers as the new velvet direction; editorial gap
- Year-round wearability case: champagne, silver, icy blue velvet for spring/summer confirmed by Zoe Report, Joyee Nails, and Marie Claire but absent from inspirational posts

**Audience blind spots:**
- What velvet nails look like *in motion* — the shifting shimmer quality is the core appeal; static images under-sell it
- "Is this too high-maintenance for me?" — real-world wear time, chip resistance, daily life longevity
- Which velvet designs photograph well vs look better in person

### Our Strategic Approach

**Differentiation:** Rather than presenting an undifferentiated gallery, we organise velvet by *design story* — dark jewel velvet, light quiet-luxury velvet, velvet design sub-categories (French tips, swirls, plaid), then practical decision-making (shape, season, office, longevity). No competitor has done this with editorial clarity for an inspirational intent reader.

**Structure plan:** Open with the finish's distinctive quality (the shift, the depth, the movement), establish the velvet-vs-cat-eye distinction sharply, curate colour stories with skin tone and occasion guidance, cover design directions as distinct choices, and close with practical reassurance questions competitors leave unanswered.

**Tone direction:** Warm editorial authority — confident taste-maker, not a technique manual.

